- What?
- Tteokbokki.

1512
00:48:31,898 --> 00:48:33,058
Really?

1513
00:48:33,458 --> 00:48:35,398
- What will we do with Sook?
- Why?

1514
00:48:35,398 --> 00:48:37,528
- She can't eat it.
- I wish I could eat it.

1515
00:48:38,268 --> 00:48:40,838
But Jae Suk didn't sound that worried.

1516
00:48:40,838 --> 00:48:41,838
Of course not.

1517
00:48:42,138 --> 00:48:44,638
- It's just that there are cameras.
- He's just saying.

1518
00:48:44,638 --> 00:48:45,638
I'm just putting it out there.

1519
00:48:45,638 --> 00:48:48,008
- "What will we do with Sook?"
- "What will we do with Sook?"

1520
00:48:48,008 --> 00:48:49,578
- He acted worried.
- You're right.

1521
00:48:50,078 --> 00:48:51,148
This is it.

1522
00:48:51,148 --> 00:48:52,248
- Yes.
- Yes.

1523
00:48:52,478 --> 00:48:54,178
- Is this it?
- I know this place.

1524
00:48:55,348 --> 00:48:56,718
It looks delicious.

1525
00:48:57,988 --> 00:48:59,188
Hello.

1526
00:48:59,658 --> 00:49:02,158
Can we eat by ourselves while filming?

1527
00:49:02,228 --> 00:49:03,358
Okay.

1528
00:49:03,358 --> 00:49:04,698
(They sit right away.)

1529
00:49:04,698 --> 00:49:07,598
We'll have 2 plates of bossam, 2 stir-fried pork,

1530
00:49:07,698 --> 00:49:10,198
- Seafood soft tofu stew.
- one seafood soft tofu stew.

1531
00:49:10,198 --> 00:49:12,238
Let's win it after some bossam.

1532
00:49:13,438 --> 00:49:15,238
I started using the stepmill.

1533
00:49:15,238 --> 00:49:16,368
- Really?
- Yes.

1534
00:49:16,638 --> 00:49:17,908
- It was tough.
- It's very hard.

1535
00:49:17,908 --> 00:49:18,908
Look at him go.

1536
00:49:18,908 --> 00:49:19,908
(Chomping down)

1537
00:49:20,338 --> 00:49:22,708
- Oh, you eat very aggressively.
- You were that hungry?

1538
00:49:23,208 --> 00:49:24,648
You didn't even dip it in ssamjang.

1539
00:49:24,648 --> 00:49:26,848
- Were you that hungry?
- He ate very aggressively.

1540
00:49:27,478 --> 00:49:28,488
This is good.

1541
00:49:28,488 --> 00:49:30,248
- Most people cut it in half...
- Yes.

1542
00:49:30,248 --> 00:49:31,518
when it's this big.

1543
00:49:32,288 --> 00:49:33,658
Don't people usually split it?

1544
00:49:36,458 --> 00:49:37,658
- You're right.
- There it is.

1545
00:49:37,658 --> 00:49:38,758
I eat this at home.

1546
00:49:38,758 --> 00:49:40,298
- They actually serve tteokbokki.
- It's very good.

1547
00:49:40,358 --> 00:49:41,798
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

1548
00:49:41,798 --> 00:49:43,898
Freshwater snail doenjang is my favorite.

1549
00:49:44,568 --> 00:49:45,968
- Thank you.
- You can...

1550
00:49:45,968 --> 00:49:47,968
- Have a piece of tteokbokki.
- Yes.

1551
00:49:47,968 --> 00:49:49,708
- That looks nice.
- That wasn't kkakdugi?

1552
00:49:49,708 --> 00:49:51,938
- It's tteokbokki.
- It looks tasty.

1553
00:49:52,508 --> 00:49:53,608
It's on the house?

1554
00:49:54,238 --> 00:49:55,648
It's delicious.

1555
00:49:56,678 --> 00:49:57,878
(She's laughing, and...)

1556
00:49:58,378 --> 00:50:01,348
Why did I make an appointment tomorrow?

1557
00:50:02,588 --> 00:50:03,948
Why did you?

1558
00:50:03,948 --> 00:50:05,058
These are all my favorites.

1559
00:50:05,058 --> 00:50:07,418
I feel bad for Sook.

1560
00:50:07,718 --> 00:50:09,458
(His eyes are set on the food.)

1561
00:50:09,458 --> 00:50:12,098
- He doesn't even mean it.
- He's only saying it.

1562
00:50:12,098 --> 00:50:13,098
(Mr. Grasshopper's insincere comfort)

1563
00:50:13,098 --> 00:50:14,458
Look at that.

1564
00:50:14,458 --> 00:50:15,798
(Their main dish arrives.)

1565
00:50:16,028 --> 00:50:17,868
Put that in a leaf wrap and eat it.

1566
00:50:17,868 --> 00:50:18,938
(Stir-fried pork is a must when eating leaf wraps.)

1567
00:50:19,268 --> 00:50:20,368
(Tender bossam and radish kimchi)

1568
00:50:20,368 --> 00:50:21,638
Look at that shrimp.

1569
00:50:22,168 --> 00:50:23,168
Seafood soft tofu stew.

1570
00:50:23,168 --> 00:50:24,938
(And seafood soft tofu stew that's pleasantly spicy)

1571
00:50:25,708 --> 00:50:27,508
- This is insane.
- This is torture for her.

1572
00:50:27,638 --> 00:50:28,848
It really is.

1573
00:50:28,848 --> 00:50:30,448
(A pie in the sky)

1574
00:50:31,178 --> 00:50:33,018
She has an endoscopy booked tomorrow.

1575
00:50:33,018 --> 00:50:35,248
Can she eat plain porridge here instead of rice?

1576
00:50:35,248 --> 00:50:36,288
- Sure.
- Good.

1577
00:50:36,288 --> 00:50:37,288
- Thank you.
- Of course.

1578
00:50:37,718 --> 00:50:39,658
(The temptation is killing her.)

1579
00:50:40,088 --> 00:50:41,758
This is the toughest ordeal for you...

1580
00:50:41,758 --> 00:50:43,188
in 2026.

1581
00:50:43,188 --> 00:50:44,588
It really is.

1582
00:50:45,358 --> 00:50:46,558
Should I cancel it?

1583
00:50:47,128 --> 00:50:48,398
- No.
- Maybe just the gastroscopy.

1584
00:50:48,398 --> 00:50:49,698
It's the grilled tofu.

1585
00:50:49,698 --> 00:50:50,928
Wrap it in leaf wraps.

1586
00:50:50,928 --> 00:50:52,538
(Eating the leaf wraps and rice in earnest)

1587
00:50:52,698 --> 00:50:53,968
- Is it 1 for each?
- Yes, it's 1 for each.

1588
00:50:53,968 --> 00:50:55,368
(Nom)

1589
00:50:55,368 --> 00:50:56,438
Thank you, ma'am.

1590
00:50:57,408 --> 00:50:59,538
(Big bite)

1591
00:51:00,578 --> 00:51:01,878
(Glancing)

1592
00:51:01,878 --> 00:51:02,878
(Grinning)

1593
00:51:02,878 --> 00:51:03,878
(A big bite for me)

1594
00:51:03,878 --> 00:51:05,418
Why do you have to take it that far?

1595
00:51:06,148 --> 00:51:07,148
What's your problem?

1596
00:51:07,148 --> 00:51:08,188
Eun I loves leaf wraps.

1597
00:51:08,188 --> 00:51:09,288
- I do.
- She does.

1598
00:51:10,648 --> 00:51:12,458
I'll just have soup.

1599
00:51:13,158 --> 00:51:14,488
It's all right.

1600
00:51:14,488 --> 00:51:15,528
- That's good.
- You can eat that.

1601
00:51:15,528 --> 00:51:17,288
(Even the soup in steamed eggs is this good.)

1602
00:51:18,258 --> 00:51:19,728
This bossam looks scrumptious.

1603
00:51:20,228 --> 00:51:21,258
It's so good.

1604
00:51:21,598 --> 00:51:23,628
Who invented medical checkups?

1605
00:51:27,538 --> 00:51:28,538
(Her plain porridge arrives to satisfy her hunger.)

1606
00:51:28,538 --> 00:51:30,268
- Seriously. This is bad.
- Look at that.

1607
00:51:33,338 --> 00:51:34,748
Poor Sook.

1608
00:51:36,748 --> 00:51:40,448
So, this is why people watch eating videos.

1609
00:51:40,448 --> 00:51:41,648
It's delicious.

1610
00:51:41,988 --> 00:51:44,048
Yeon Shik knows how to enjoy leaf wraps and rice.

1611
00:51:44,148 --> 00:51:45,158
I like it.

1612
00:51:45,158 --> 00:51:46,558
- You do?
- Yes.

1613
00:51:46,818 --> 00:51:49,328
- I like leaf wraps and rice.
- It makes me happy.

1614
00:51:50,088 --> 00:51:52,228
He's more easy-going than I thought.

1615
00:51:52,228 --> 00:51:54,158
- Am I?
- You're a good guy.

1616
00:51:54,158 --> 00:51:55,328
- Really?
- I thought he'd be cold.

1617
00:51:55,328 --> 00:51:56,898
- No, he's not.
- Really?

1618
00:51:56,898 --> 00:51:59,038
He's like a handsome version of Lee Kwang Soo.

1619
00:51:59,038 --> 00:52:00,738
(He's like a handsome version of Lee Kwang Soo.)

1620
00:52:01,198 --> 00:52:02,568
What does that make Kwang Soo?

1621
00:52:02,968 --> 00:52:04,338
If he's the handsome version of Kwang Soo...

1622
00:52:04,568 --> 00:52:06,638
I think they have similar personalities.

1623
00:52:06,638 --> 00:52:07,838
(The two honorary comedians have similar personalities.)

1624
00:52:07,878 --> 00:52:10,108
I think we have pretty good teamwork in games, though.

1625
00:52:10,148 --> 00:52:11,278
We played pretty well.

1626
00:52:11,518 --> 00:52:14,278
When did you three first meet?

1627
00:52:14,278 --> 00:52:15,518
In 1995?

1628
00:52:15,518 --> 00:52:17,488
- Sook entered in 1995.
- You...

1629
00:52:17,488 --> 00:52:18,618
I entered in 1991.

1630
00:52:18,758 --> 00:52:20,518
- Eun I...
- In 1993. She entered in 1995.

1631
00:52:20,518 --> 00:52:21,528
I joined in 1995.

1632
00:52:22,188 --> 00:52:23,588
It's been over 30 years.

1633
00:52:23,728 --> 00:52:25,658
And we're still friends to this day.

1634
00:52:28,058 --> 00:52:30,698
Not long ago, I cried.

1635
00:52:31,328 --> 00:52:33,038
- You cried?
- I hate crying, you know.

1636
00:52:33,868 --> 00:52:35,168
It was at the year-end awards ceremony.

1637
00:52:36,038 --> 00:52:38,238
Eun I has always rooted for me every year.

1638
00:52:38,508 --> 00:52:40,678
"Sook, you can win the Grand Award."

1639
00:52:40,678 --> 00:52:42,148
"You'll win the Grand Award this year!"

1640
00:52:42,148 --> 00:52:43,578
She's always supported me.

1641
00:52:44,308 --> 00:52:46,748
But they announce the winner of the Top Excellence Award first.

1642
00:52:47,518 --> 00:52:49,218
"The Top Excellence Award goes to..."

1643
00:52:49,548 --> 00:52:50,848
"Song Eun I!"

1644
00:52:50,848 --> 00:52:51,958
Yes, she won it.

1645
00:52:51,958 --> 00:52:53,158
And she was like,

1646
00:52:53,458 --> 00:52:54,488
"Me?"

1647
00:52:54,488 --> 00:52:56,858
She was so startled.

1648
00:52:56,858 --> 00:52:59,228
- I didn't know I was nominated.
- Yes, she went up the stage...

1649
00:52:59,228 --> 00:53:00,428
and talked.

1650
00:53:00,428 --> 00:53:02,068
She's always rooted for me,

1651
00:53:03,398 --> 00:53:06,398
and she won that award for the first time in 33 years.

1652
00:53:06,398 --> 00:53:09,438
Yes. It was my first time receiving an award on the stage in KBS.

1653
00:53:10,968 --> 00:53:12,208
You must have been touched.

1654
00:53:12,208 --> 00:53:13,508
- I was so touched.
- Yes.

1655
00:53:13,938 --> 00:53:14,948
Let's go for the Grand Award next time.

1656
00:53:15,648 --> 00:53:16,678
How would I?

1657
00:53:17,978 --> 00:53:20,148
- Hey, you...
- How can I?

1658
00:53:20,148 --> 00:53:22,088
- You have to find a way.
- No.

1659
00:53:22,088 --> 00:53:24,748
She really doesn't have much luck with awards.

1660
00:53:24,748 --> 00:53:26,088
She never even won the Best Rookie Award.

1661
00:53:26,388 --> 00:53:27,858
When she was so confident.

1662
00:53:27,858 --> 00:53:29,488
- You didn't win one?
- No.

1663
00:53:30,028 --> 00:53:32,698
When people thought I was pretty funny,

1664
00:53:33,158 --> 00:53:34,558
Hye Lyun swooped in out of nowhere.

1665
00:53:34,558 --> 00:53:35,798
(Hye Lyun appeared like a comet.)

1666
00:53:35,798 --> 00:53:37,598
- It was bad timing.
- Yes.

1667
00:53:37,598 --> 00:53:39,338
- Winning awards...
- She was pretty funny.

1668
00:53:39,338 --> 00:53:40,338
is related to luck.

1669
00:53:40,338 --> 00:53:42,168
I wasn't so bad, but Hye Lyun was hilarious.

1670
00:53:43,138 --> 00:53:45,808
When I was nominated for the Best Rookie Award,

1671
00:53:45,808 --> 00:53:46,808
I got a tailored suit.

1672
00:53:47,478 --> 00:53:49,148
- And I didn't win it.
- Hey.

1673
00:53:49,848 --> 00:53:50,908
He went way over his budget...

1674
00:53:50,908 --> 00:53:52,578
and got a custom Dolce and Gabbana suit.

1675
00:53:52,818 --> 00:53:54,518
- To win the Best Rookie Award?
- Yes.

1676
00:53:54,518 --> 00:53:55,718
He was a senior at the time,

1677
00:53:55,918 --> 00:53:58,018
so I asked, "You actually bought this?"

1678
00:53:58,018 --> 00:54:00,088
- It turned out he had bought 2.
- He bought 2 suits?

1679
00:54:00,088 --> 00:54:01,758
It was velvet. Right?

1680
00:54:02,928 --> 00:54:05,358
- It was kind of burgundy...
- Don't say that.

1681
00:54:05,358 --> 00:54:07,798
- Burgundy?
- A burgundy, velvet suit.

1682
00:54:07,798 --> 00:54:09,628
And I never won that award.

1683
00:54:09,628 --> 00:54:11,168
- The installment...
- Paying it off was so...

1684
00:54:11,168 --> 00:54:12,398
It was like a 24-month payment installment.

1685
00:54:12,398 --> 00:54:13,438
(He became a gentleman paying off two suits.)

1686
00:54:13,438 --> 00:54:14,438
It was so tough.

1687
00:54:14,438 --> 00:54:15,938
None of us won the Best Rookie Award.

1688
00:54:15,938 --> 00:54:16,938
- No one.
- No one.

1689
00:54:16,938 --> 00:54:18,168
I never won the Best Rookie Award either.

1690
00:54:18,168 --> 00:54:20,038
- You didn't?
- No.

1691
00:54:20,038 --> 00:54:22,178
I was nominated,

1692
00:54:22,178 --> 00:54:24,778
but Jung Seok won it for his performance as Nab-ddeuk.

1693
00:54:24,778 --> 00:54:25,848
- Oh, that makes sense.
- I see.

1694
00:54:25,848 --> 00:54:27,048
- That's a tough one to beat.
- From the same movie.

1695
00:54:27,048 --> 00:54:28,818
- That one makes sense.
- It does.

1696
00:54:28,818 --> 00:54:29,918
- Right.
- It makes sense now.

1697
00:54:29,918 --> 00:54:31,688
- You won the Best Rookie Award.
- What?

1698
00:54:31,688 --> 00:54:32,718
Me?

1699
00:54:32,918 --> 00:54:34,688
- Oh, in the Variety Category.
- Oh, gosh.

1700
00:54:34,688 --> 00:54:36,028
In the Variety Category?

1701
00:54:36,028 --> 00:54:37,658
I did. I won the Best Rookie Award in the Variety Category.

1702
00:54:37,658 --> 00:54:38,898
He's the only one who won it.

1703
00:54:38,898 --> 00:54:40,198
You're the only one among us!

1704
00:54:40,198 --> 00:54:41,198
You're right. I did win one.

1705
00:54:41,198 --> 00:54:43,998
Come to think of it, I won one as Yoo San Seul on MBC.

1706
00:54:44,398 --> 00:54:46,398
- Right. Yoo San Seul.
- As Yoo San Seul.

1707
00:54:46,398 --> 00:54:47,638
You did.

1708
00:54:47,738 --> 00:54:49,038
I was probably over 50 when I did.

1709
00:54:49,838 --> 00:54:51,308
(A late Best Rookie Award)

1710
00:54:51,308 --> 00:54:52,338
- As San Seul.
- That's funny.

1711
00:54:52,338 --> 00:54:53,478
- The Best Rookie Award.
- Yes.

1712
00:54:54,238 --> 00:54:56,308
I'm sorry to bring this up while you eat, Sook,

1713
00:54:56,308 --> 00:54:58,048
but you also have to play the game of deciding who pays.

1714
00:54:59,618 --> 00:55:00,848
But I didn't eat anything.

1715
00:55:00,848 --> 00:55:02,048
- You have to.
- But you ate...

1716
00:55:02,188 --> 00:55:03,248
This is just soup.

1717
00:55:03,288 --> 00:55:05,618
You ate soup and some steamed eggs.

1718
00:55:06,058 --> 00:55:07,558
- Sorry.
- You guys are strict.

1719
00:55:07,558 --> 00:55:09,658
That's the group life.

1720
00:55:10,128 --> 00:55:11,858
What a rip-off.

1721
00:55:13,128 --> 00:55:14,628
- Are you done eating?
- Yes.

1722
00:55:14,628 --> 00:55:16,268
You seem less angry now.

1723
00:55:16,268 --> 00:55:17,898
- I feel better now.
- Yes, she looks better.

1724
00:55:18,068 --> 00:55:19,438
- What should we play?
- What is it?

1725
00:55:19,438 --> 00:55:21,098
- What do we play?
- What game should we play?

1726
00:55:21,398 --> 00:55:23,308
We'll pour some water on a spoon,

1727
00:55:23,308 --> 00:55:24,868
- The one who knocks it off loses?
- and the one who knocks it off...

1728
00:55:24,868 --> 00:55:26,278
- Yes, let's play that.
- How about playing this game?

1729
00:55:26,978 --> 00:55:28,208
- Sounds good.
- Yes.

1730
00:55:28,208 --> 00:55:29,678
- Let's use a new spoon.
- Let's do it here.

1731
00:55:29,678 --> 00:55:30,848
- Let's go in this order.
- Sure.

1732
00:55:30,848 --> 00:55:31,978
This order. Are you okay with the order?

1733
00:55:31,978 --> 00:55:33,018
Sure.

1734
00:55:33,148 --> 00:55:34,478
This is such a rip-off.

1735
00:55:34,478 --> 00:55:36,418
- Just play.
- All right.

1736
00:55:39,518 --> 00:55:40,618
If you knock off the spoon, you lose.

1737
00:55:40,618 --> 00:55:42,128
- All right.
- Knocking off the spoon?

1738
00:55:42,128 --> 00:55:43,658
- Yes.
- Yes, it's the spoon.

1739
00:55:44,188 --> 00:55:45,258
It has to be the spoon.

1740
00:55:48,468 --> 00:55:50,128
So, it's okay if the water falls.

1741
00:55:50,428 --> 00:55:52,438
Why would you take such a risk?

1742
00:55:54,838 --> 00:55:56,508
It's going to happen soon.

1743
00:55:56,508 --> 00:55:58,138
- Yes, it's soon.
- It's soon.

1744
00:55:58,138 --> 00:55:59,938
(The spoon gets heavier.)

1745
00:56:00,478 --> 00:56:01,608
Here we go, Mr. Grasshopper.

1746
00:56:01,608 --> 00:56:03,808
- I bet it's Jae Suk.
- Yes, it's happening.

1747
00:56:04,978 --> 00:56:06,318
Why is your hand trembling so much?

1748
00:56:06,978 --> 00:56:08,888
- You just dropped a lot.
- He gets nervous...

1749
00:56:08,888 --> 00:56:10,418
- as soon as it's the real game.
- Why is it shaking so much?

1750
00:56:10,418 --> 00:56:11,588
- What's wrong with you?
- That's funny.

1751
00:56:12,118 --> 00:56:14,788
- The countdown begins.
- Here we go.

1752
00:56:15,988 --> 00:56:17,088
Almost there.

1753
00:56:17,388 --> 00:56:19,198
The handle lifted up a bit.

1754
00:56:20,058 --> 00:56:21,928
- It's slightly up.
- Finish it, Yeon Seok.

1755
00:56:21,928 --> 00:56:23,128
- All it takes is a drop now.
- Finish it.

1756
00:56:23,398 --> 00:56:24,468
- Finish it.
- Finish it.

1757
00:56:24,468 --> 00:56:26,168
It'll be so funny if you lose.

1758
00:56:26,798 --> 00:56:28,068
Stop acting up.

1759
00:56:32,278 --> 00:56:33,508
Come on.

1760
00:56:37,848 --> 00:56:39,218
(Yeon Seok passes.)

1761
00:56:39,278 --> 00:56:40,918
- All right.
- The water drops are falling.

1762
00:56:43,918 --> 00:56:45,288
It's up!

1763
00:56:46,988 --> 00:56:48,388
It's up!

1764
00:56:48,588 --> 00:56:50,628
It's Mr. Grasshopper's turn now.

1765
00:56:50,928 --> 00:56:53,228
- I think I'm safe.
- It's Mr. Grasshopper.

1766
00:56:53,228 --> 00:56:54,728
- It's only one drop of water now.
- I'm safe.

1767
00:56:54,728 --> 00:56:55,828
- It's...
- I'm safe.

1768
00:56:55,828 --> 00:56:57,528
- You're not safe.
- Oh, my gosh.

1769
00:56:57,668 --> 00:56:58,998
I put it halfway up there.

1770
00:56:58,998 --> 00:57:01,268
(The miracle of one drop of water)

1771
00:57:03,568 --> 00:57:04,608
Hurry up and do it.

1772
00:57:08,378 --> 00:57:09,378
Oh, gosh.

1773
00:57:11,408 --> 00:57:12,448
Oh, gosh.

1774
00:57:14,478 --> 00:57:15,888
(Jae Suk loses.)

1775
00:57:15,888 --> 00:57:16,888
Let's get out of here.

1776
00:57:17,148 --> 00:57:18,218
- Let's go.
- That makes me so mad.

1777
00:57:18,218 --> 00:57:19,418
- Thanks for the food.
- Thanks for the food.

1778
00:57:19,558 --> 00:57:20,688
How are you so bad at games?

1779
00:57:20,688 --> 00:57:22,488
- I'm so angry.
- Thanks for the food.

1780
00:57:24,258 --> 00:57:25,458
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

1781
00:57:25,458 --> 00:57:27,228
- Goodbye, sir.
- Have a good day.

1782
00:57:27,798 --> 00:57:29,298
We're taking the bus, right?

1783
00:57:29,298 --> 00:57:30,368
We have to take the bus.

1784
00:57:31,268 --> 00:57:32,368
It's right outside.

1785
00:57:32,598 --> 00:57:34,338
- Here?
- It'll be here in two minutes.

1786
00:57:34,798 --> 00:57:36,708
I'll show you this time.

1787
00:57:36,708 --> 00:57:37,768
Show us what?

1788
00:57:38,238 --> 00:57:39,238
- I...
- Okay.

1789
00:57:39,238 --> 00:57:40,338
Show us. Let's go.

1790
00:57:40,508 --> 00:57:42,008
Jae Suk says he'll show us.

1791
00:57:42,008 --> 00:57:43,808
(Not interested)

1792
00:57:44,648 --> 00:57:46,218
- I don't know.
- Who are you talking to?

1793
00:57:46,218 --> 00:57:48,078
Maybe he'll show us his front teeth.

1794
00:57:49,048 --> 00:57:50,488
- It's already here.
- Bus 271.

1795
00:57:50,788 --> 00:57:52,618
- Here it is.
- Here it is.

1796
00:57:53,258 --> 00:57:55,018
- Hello.
- Hello.

1797
00:57:55,358 --> 00:57:57,058
- Hello.
- Four adults.

1798
00:57:57,058 --> 00:57:58,128
(What's the second spare time spot they'll go by bus?)

1799
00:57:58,128 --> 00:57:59,958
- Thank you.
- Hello.

1800
00:58:00,698 --> 00:58:02,268
Maeng Gwan Yeong.

1801
00:58:02,268 --> 00:58:03,298
Gwan Yeong.

1802
00:58:03,298 --> 00:58:04,968
"Just by the sound of a ring,"

1803
00:58:04,968 --> 00:58:07,068
"I can diagnose any symptom."

1804
00:58:07,068 --> 00:58:09,568
"I'm the Sangam-dong Specialist."

1805
00:58:09,908 --> 00:58:12,408
"From comprehensive checkups and high-difficulty surgeries..."

1806
00:58:12,408 --> 00:58:13,508
"to professional cleaning!"

1807
00:58:13,508 --> 00:58:14,938
- "Introducing..."
- What?

1808
00:58:14,938 --> 00:58:17,278
"our very own general hospital where every level of care is possible."

1809
00:58:17,278 --> 00:58:18,308
A general hospital?

1810
00:58:18,308 --> 00:58:19,418
Just by the sound of a ring?

1811
00:58:19,418 --> 00:58:20,678
Or it's about bicycles.

1812
00:58:20,948 --> 00:58:22,848
Oh, a bicycle repair shop.

1813
00:58:22,848 --> 00:58:24,418
- That could be it.
- Right.

1814
00:58:24,788 --> 00:58:26,388
- Happy New Year.
- Goodbye.

1815
00:58:26,388 --> 00:58:27,688
Happy New Year.

1816
00:58:28,888 --> 00:58:29,928
What?

1817
00:58:30,158 --> 00:58:31,998
- Where are we?
- He's looking.

1818
00:58:31,998 --> 00:58:34,298
- This isn't it?
- There's an entrance nearby.

1819
00:58:34,458 --> 00:58:36,298
- An entrance? In the market?
- Where?

1820
00:58:36,668 --> 00:58:37,698
This is...

1821
00:58:37,698 --> 00:58:38,838
Mapo Agricultural and Marine Products Market.

1822
00:58:38,838 --> 00:58:40,368
- This is it.
- This is the one.

1823
00:58:40,698 --> 00:58:42,138
The entrance is next to it.

1824
00:58:42,338 --> 00:58:44,568
- Next to it?
- I think it's this way.

1825
00:58:44,568 --> 00:58:45,878
Yes, let's get there first.

1826
00:58:45,878 --> 00:58:47,508
(They walk toward the market.)

1827
00:58:47,778 --> 00:58:49,348
What does he mean by "the gate on the right?"

1828
00:58:49,508 --> 00:58:50,548
Is that...

1829
00:58:50,948 --> 00:58:52,678
How do I get there?

1830
00:58:53,048 --> 00:58:54,548
Yeon Shik, did you turn on the GPS?

1831
00:58:55,048 --> 00:58:56,418
But this is 251.

1832
00:58:56,788 --> 00:58:58,388
- What?
- What?

1833
00:58:59,258 --> 00:59:00,688
It's 251, World Cup-ro.

1834
00:59:00,688 --> 00:59:02,488
(He checks the map again.)

1835
00:59:02,488 --> 00:59:04,058
Is there a certain shop?

1836
00:59:04,058 --> 00:59:05,228
This is so funny.

1837
00:59:05,328 --> 00:59:07,228
Isn't it about time one of us searched it too?

1838
00:59:07,228 --> 00:59:08,398
No, let him do it.

1839
00:59:09,028 --> 00:59:10,498
- We can't...
- There are...

1840
00:59:10,498 --> 00:59:11,998
three people, and we all have our hands in our pockets.

1841
00:59:12,138 --> 00:59:14,468
- It's better to have one do it.
- The youngest...

1842
00:59:14,668 --> 00:59:16,168
is good at this stuff.

1843
00:59:16,408 --> 00:59:17,508
Is it that building?

1844
00:59:17,508 --> 00:59:19,238
- Which building?
- Is it that way?

1845
00:59:19,238 --> 00:59:20,308
- Do we go that way?
- Let's go.

1846
00:59:20,308 --> 00:59:21,308
Hold on!

1847
00:59:21,308 --> 00:59:22,308
(They instantly start walking.)

1848
00:59:22,578 --> 00:59:24,248
There aren't any buildings around here.

1849
00:59:24,248 --> 00:59:27,218
- Do, re, mi - Do, re, mi

1850
00:59:27,348 --> 00:59:28,378
- Are you sure those are the notes?
- Do, re, mi

1851
00:59:28,378 --> 00:59:29,788
- No, we're just doing it.
- No?

1852
00:59:30,188 --> 00:59:31,388
Isn't that the one?

1853
00:59:31,388 --> 00:59:33,288
- Wait, I see something!
- Is that it?

1854
00:59:33,288 --> 00:59:34,288
(They see a pack of bicycles?)

1855
00:59:34,318 --> 00:59:36,058
I see a lot of bicycles there.

1856
00:59:36,058 --> 00:59:37,088
- That must be it.
- That's it.

1857
00:59:37,088 --> 00:59:38,088
I see a group of bicycles.

1858
00:59:38,088 --> 00:59:39,558
That has to be it.

1859
00:59:39,858 --> 00:59:41,058
- This is it.
- This is it.

1860
00:59:41,058 --> 00:59:42,328
- Oh, here it is.
- We found it.

1861
00:59:42,328 --> 00:59:43,628
Check this out!

1862
00:59:43,628 --> 00:59:46,038
- Goodness. That's so many.
- Goodness.

1863
00:59:46,598 --> 00:59:48,568
There are so many bicycles.

1864
00:59:48,568 --> 00:59:49,868
(Just around the corner, it's filled with Ttareungis.)

1865
00:59:49,868 --> 00:59:51,238
I've never seen this many before.

1866
00:59:51,238 --> 00:59:53,008
How many are these?

1867
00:59:53,008 --> 00:59:54,138
(Ttareungis are Seoul's public bicycles.)

1868
00:59:54,378 --> 00:59:55,948
There's more back there.

1869
00:59:55,948 --> 00:59:57,378
(There are Ttareungis everywhere.)

1870
00:59:57,378 --> 00:59:58,778
That's so many.

1871
00:59:59,478 --> 01:00:02,388
He said to come through the door on the right.

1872
01:00:02,818 --> 01:00:04,018
Maeng Gwan Yeong.

1873
01:00:04,318 --> 01:00:06,158
- Maeng Gwan Yeong?
- Gwan Yeong.

1874
01:00:06,158 --> 01:00:08,018
- Hello.
- Hi. There you are.

1875
01:00:08,018 --> 01:00:10,088
- Where?
- Are you Mr. Maeng Gwan Yeong?

1876
01:00:10,158 --> 01:00:11,788
- Yes, that's me.
- Good to meet you.

1877
01:00:11,788 --> 01:00:13,498
- We found him.
- Nice to meet you.

1878
01:00:13,498 --> 01:00:14,558
- Hello.
- It's a pleasure.

1879
01:00:14,558 --> 01:00:15,968
- Hello.
- Hello.

1880
01:00:16,198 --> 01:00:17,498
(Maeng Gwan Yeong, the second Whenever Guest)

1881
01:00:17,498 --> 01:00:19,538
There are so many Ttareungis here!

1882
01:00:20,368 --> 01:00:23,308
Is this where Ttareungis are stored and released?

1883
01:00:23,468 --> 01:00:24,768
Yes, you're right.

1884
01:00:24,838 --> 01:00:28,508
We mostly deal with bicycles in the Gangbuk area.

1885
01:00:29,208 --> 01:00:32,818
The Ttareungis in the Gangbuk area are repaired...

1886
01:00:33,078 --> 01:00:35,888
and checked here before they're released.

1887
01:00:35,888 --> 01:00:37,288
Yes, in a word, it's a hospital.

1888
01:00:37,288 --> 01:00:38,518
- A hospital.
- A general hospital.

1889
01:00:38,518 --> 01:00:39,858
- A general hospital for Ttareungis.
- You're right.

1890
01:00:39,858 --> 01:00:41,758
- He's right.
- Just by the sound of a ring...

1891
01:00:42,028 --> 01:00:43,558
- Hello.
- Hello.

1892
01:00:43,558 --> 01:00:45,228
- Hello.
- Hello.

1893
01:00:45,228 --> 01:00:47,628
(Kim Dae Uk and Im Min Oh, the Ttareungi mechanics)

1894
01:00:47,628 --> 01:00:50,198
I see you have these helping you with work.

1895
01:00:50,198 --> 01:00:51,328
They have wheels on them.

1896
01:00:51,328 --> 01:00:52,798
- The chairs have wheels.
- That's so interesting.

1897
01:00:52,798 --> 01:00:54,098
- Are these wheels?
- What are these?

1898
01:00:54,098 --> 01:00:55,098
- Yes.
- Goodness.

1899
01:00:55,098 --> 01:00:56,738
- They can slide on it.
- Oh, it's...

1900
01:00:56,738 --> 01:00:58,908
- It's a work stool.
- Yes, it's a work stool.

1901
01:00:58,908 --> 01:01:01,238
I see. To grab the tools.

1902
01:01:01,708 --> 01:01:02,848
This would be...

1903
01:01:02,978 --> 01:01:04,708
This is so fun.

1904
01:01:04,848 --> 01:01:06,248
Did you make it yourself?

1905
01:01:06,548 --> 01:01:08,178
- We bought the stools...
- We bought the stools...

1906
01:01:08,178 --> 01:01:10,018
- and only attached the wheels.
- and put the wheels.

1907
01:01:10,018 --> 01:01:11,958
Putting wheels on them is a piece of cake for them.

1908
01:01:11,958 --> 01:01:13,758
- This is nothing.
- Right.

1909
01:01:13,758 --> 01:01:14,788
They're customized.

1910
01:01:14,788 --> 01:01:15,828
- You're right.
- Exactly.

1911
01:01:15,828 --> 01:01:17,628
By the way,

1912
01:01:17,628 --> 01:01:19,828
how many bicycles come here in a day?

1913
01:01:20,198 --> 01:01:21,898
At best,

1914
01:01:21,898 --> 01:01:23,998
it's around 300.

1915
01:01:25,538 --> 01:01:27,668
Is it just these three, or are there more?

1916
01:01:27,668 --> 01:01:29,968
- There are more employees.
- I see.

1917
01:01:29,968 --> 01:01:31,408
- But it's lunchtime.
- It's lunchtime, so...

1918
01:01:31,408 --> 01:01:33,438
Oh, that's why...

1919
01:01:33,638 --> 01:01:35,608
You asked us to come during lunchtime.

1920
01:01:35,708 --> 01:01:36,848
It's literally a spare time.

1921
01:01:36,848 --> 01:01:40,218
- I've ridden a Ttareungi before, - Right.

1922
01:01:40,218 --> 01:01:41,748
but it never occurred to me that there would be people...

1923
01:01:41,748 --> 01:01:43,148
- fixing these.
- Indeed.

1924
01:01:43,348 --> 01:01:47,388
Not many people are aware of what we do here.

1925
01:01:47,388 --> 01:01:50,088
But we do our best to repair these bikes...

1926
01:01:50,088 --> 01:01:52,658
for those who love Ttareungi.

1927
01:01:53,328 --> 01:01:56,098
That's why I applied,

1928
01:01:56,498 --> 01:01:59,138
and it's such an honorable day for me.

1929
01:01:59,398 --> 01:02:00,398
Really?

1930
01:02:00,398 --> 01:02:03,238
I'm sure there are numerous failures,

1931
01:02:03,238 --> 01:02:05,838
but which part is broken the most often?

1932
01:02:05,938 --> 01:02:07,838
- The wheels, - Wheels.

1933
01:02:07,838 --> 01:02:09,208
the tubes,

1934
01:02:09,578 --> 01:02:11,308
and the brakes.

1935
01:02:11,308 --> 01:02:13,148
I see.

1936
01:02:13,148 --> 01:02:14,978
We always do our best to maintain the parts...

1937
01:02:14,978 --> 01:02:17,148
that are directly related to safety.

1938
01:02:17,148 --> 01:02:18,388
(They work meticulously as it's related to safety.)

1939
01:02:18,388 --> 01:02:19,888
Were there any absurd stories?

1940
01:02:20,118 --> 01:02:23,058
Someone had loaded one of the bikes with delicious food...

1941
01:02:23,288 --> 01:02:24,428
- and spilled it.
- Yes.

1942
01:02:24,428 --> 01:02:26,828
For instance, tteokbokki.

1943
01:02:27,458 --> 01:02:29,768
Oh, they should have wiped it off before they left.

1944
01:02:30,368 --> 01:02:31,798
When it stays there for too long...

1945
01:02:31,798 --> 01:02:33,098
- It sticks, right?
- Right.

1946
01:02:33,098 --> 01:02:35,298
It was very difficult to remove it.

1947
01:02:35,298 --> 01:02:37,408
- Cleaning them must be tough.
- Right.

1948
01:02:37,408 --> 01:02:40,278
Because they get in between the parts.

1949
01:02:40,278 --> 01:02:42,178
Did anyone steal the seats?

1950
01:02:42,378 --> 01:02:45,048
- Fortunately, there weren't any.
- I...

1951
01:02:45,048 --> 01:02:46,518
What made you curious about that?

1952
01:02:46,848 --> 01:02:49,488
When I was little, I bought a 200-dollar bike...

1953
01:02:49,488 --> 01:02:51,918
after saving up for so long,

1954
01:02:51,918 --> 01:02:54,488
and tied it to a utility pole.

1955
01:02:54,658 --> 01:02:56,288
And someone had stolen my seat.

1956
01:02:56,558 --> 01:02:58,428
So, I had to ride it home, standing up.

1957
01:02:58,898 --> 01:03:01,198
There were many bicycle thieves when we were little.

1958
01:03:01,198 --> 01:03:02,998
- There were some.
- There were.

1959
01:03:02,998 --> 01:03:05,538
Yes, some would even take the front wheel.

1960
01:03:05,798 --> 01:03:07,268
Are there tandem bikes?

1961
01:03:07,598 --> 01:03:08,698
I'm afraid not.

1962
01:03:08,698 --> 01:03:09,808
- No?
- No.

1963
01:03:09,808 --> 01:03:11,008
Why do you want to ride it with?

1964
01:03:12,278 --> 01:03:13,408
Who is it for?

1965
01:03:13,778 --> 01:03:15,338
(Terrified)

1966
01:03:15,338 --> 01:03:17,308
- I just...
- This isn't the time for that.

1967
01:03:18,178 --> 01:03:19,578
It's exactly the time for that!

1968
01:03:19,578 --> 01:03:20,878
- What?
- It's not the right time.

1969
01:03:21,618 --> 01:03:22,888
- It's exactly the time for that!
- You won the Best Rookie Award...

1970
01:03:22,888 --> 01:03:24,248
in the Variety Category.

1971
01:03:24,248 --> 01:03:26,258
- You should be...
- I'm old enough to do that.

1972
01:03:26,258 --> 01:03:27,688
focusing more on work.

1973
01:03:27,688 --> 01:03:29,188
- You should focus more on work.
- Yes, you still have time.

1974
01:03:29,188 --> 01:03:30,828
You'll realize what life is once you turn 50.

1975
01:03:30,828 --> 01:03:32,328
(He's in his 40s, so he knows nothing yet.)

1976
01:03:32,458 --> 01:03:34,398
Do you own personal bikes as well?

1977
01:03:34,798 --> 01:03:36,628
I have a few. Like ten bikes.

1978
01:03:36,628 --> 01:03:37,768
- What?
- What?

1979
01:03:38,528 --> 01:03:40,198
They may seem similar, but...

1980
01:03:40,198 --> 01:03:41,838
- But they're all different.
- Yes.

1981
01:03:41,838 --> 01:03:43,268
(No two bikes under the sun are the same.)

1982
01:03:43,268 --> 01:03:44,338
That's interesting.

1983
01:03:44,338 --> 01:03:45,338
How fascinating!

1984
01:03:45,338 --> 01:03:46,378
(The Whenever Guest loves bicycles.)

1985
01:03:46,378 --> 01:03:48,438
We would even go on bike tours.

1986
01:03:48,438 --> 01:03:49,648
- Oh, I see.
- Yes.

1987
01:03:49,648 --> 01:03:51,348
- You also go on bike tours?
- Yes.

